HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1133
By Lamberth
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Edgar "Ed" Joines
Cochran of Englewood.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Edgar "Ed" Joines Cochran of Englewood; and
WHEREAS, Ed Cochran was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in
numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, born on October 31, 1943, Mr. Cochran was the son of Hubert Cochran and
Zeola Stiles Cochran in Englewood, where he was raised in a home with eight siblings; and
WHEREAS, Ed Cochran began working at Bain and Holden Tire Company at the age of
eleven and continued there throughout his teenage years and into early adulthood; he
graduated from Englewood High School in 1963 and later worked for B.F. Goodrich and J.M.
Huber before starting his own business; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Cochran met the love of his life, Nancy Gentry, after she challenged him
to a drag race on Etowah's Tennessee Avenue in the summer of 1967; while the winner of the
race is debated to this day, the two were engaged within six weeks, married in six months, and
never looked back; and
WHEREAS, over the next fifty-eight years, they started and ran a successful business,
managed a small family farm, raised four children, and lovingly spoiled four grandchildren; and
WHEREAS, perhaps best known as a local business owner in Englewood, Ed Cochran
managed Ed's Grocery for thirty-five years from 1970 to 2005; for more than twenty of those
years, his was the only grocery store in town; and
HJR1133
015810
- 1 -

WHEREAS, with his white butcher's apron tied neatly around his waist, Mr. Cochran
could be found Monday through Saturday serving the people in the town he loved; and
WHEREAS, for him, the grocery store was more than a business—it was a ministry
through which he showed the love of God to others, and it was his mission that no one in
Englewood go hungry; and
WHEREAS, accompanying Ed Cochran's passion for the grocery business was his love
of farming, but more specifically, his love of farming atop Chestnut Ridge in Nonaburg, a
location where he had longed to live since childhood and described as "the prettiest place on
Earth"; and
WHEREAS, over a number of decades, Mr. Cochran worked tirelessly to fulfill his dream
of building back his family's farm, and he even took the dream a little further by expanding it with
his children and beloved grandchildren; and
WHEREAS, though faced with his fair share of trials and aversity, Ed Cochran lived a life
overwhelmingly defined by God's blessings—a loving wife of nearly six decades, four children
who adored him, and four grandchildren who were his absolute pride and joy; most importantly,
Mr. Cochran knew Jesus, which means his story does not end on this Earth and his legacy
continues; and
WHEREAS, he will be sadly mourned but fondly remembered by his wife, Nancy
Cochran; children, Kim (Todd) Cochran-Graham, Mike Cochran, Karen (Justin) Baker, and
State Representative Mark Cochran; grandchildren, Melia Baker, Kellan Baker, McCain Baker,
and Reagan Baker; siblings, Huberta Williams, Twila Chrisman, Dorcas Carter, Jean
McDermott, June Cochran, and Doug Cochran; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his parents, Ed Cochran was preceded in death by his
siblings, DeLayne Cochran and Gail Anderson; and
- 2 - 015810

WHEREAS, Mr. Cochran leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should remember the
bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Edgar "Ed" Joines Cochran, reflecting fondly
upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with
courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Cochran.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
